Let us denote a continuous geophysical field in space and time ?(t,r), where t and r denote time and space, respectively. A sampled discrete or (spatially and/or temporally) averaged measurement x of this field is then given by the random variable x.

The mapping function h relates the true geophysical field to the actual measurement. The error is then defined as the difference between the sampled observation and the true, but unknown, state of the geophysical field.

A reference data set containing measurements y of the same geophysical variable with spatiotemporal resolution ß, which might be sampled in different ways at different times, may be The difference between the two samples is then obviously given as
For validation purposes, one is not primarily interested in the differences for each individual pair of observations, but the underlying probability density function (PDF) of , which is defined as

The uncertainty assessment requires detailed understanding of the individual contributions to the PDF:
  • Systematic effects due to individual measurement devices and retrieval procedures (h,k), including large-scale systematic effects due to instrument calibration or harmonization
  • Random measurement and retrieval errors
  • Differences in the representativeness of different data sets (again including random and systematic components)
If all these different components are fully understood, one can develop an error model M that allows to predict the PDF of d as a function of the above mentioned factors.

The statistical properties of d, i.e., the differences between the considered data sets, are commonly expressed in terms of the corresponding zeroth and first-order moments (mean, variance and covariance), and can be used to derive uncertainty estimates for these products. The variance of is defined as

In full analogy to the mean and variance of the difference ??, one can define the corresponding properties for the two observational data sets x and y, as well as their associated error and . We can also define the covariance between the data sets as a measure for their statistical dependency as
The most common metric to quantify relative systematic differences between data sets is the bias, which is defined as the difference in the mean values.
The median md is a value separating the higher half from the lower half of a data set.
The root-mean-square deviation RMSD is a metric for characterizing the pairwise agreement between two data sets.
The RMSD can be decomposed into two bias related terms (a bias in mean and a bias in standard deviation) and a correlation-dependent term.

The correlation between two data sets is a normalized measure of statistical dependency between two variables. The linear (Pearson) product-moment correlation coefficient is a correlation metric, which describes first-order linear statistical dependency as the covariance between the data sets normalized by their respective standard deviations.

The nonparametric Spearman’s rank correlation coefficient is a nonlinear correlation metric. Its definition is very similar to that of the Pearson correlation coefficient with the exception that it uses the variances and covariance of the ranks (r) of the data sets rather than the values directly.

Kendall’s t is another nonparametric, nonlinear correlation metric, which is mostly used as hypothesis test whether two variables are statistically dependent rather than for quantifying the quality of a regression.

Mutual information takes into account only general statistical dependencies without any specific assumption of the corresponding functional form. It is defined based upon the probability distributions of the data sets.
